Exercise Quality prediction

Report by Carlos Neves

for Practical Machine learning course.

Introduction

Using devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit it is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal activity relatively inexpensively. These type of devices are part of the quantified self movement – a group of enthusiasts who take measurements about themselves regularly to improve their health, to find patterns in their behaviour, or because they are tech geeks. One thing that people regularly do is quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but they rarely quantify how well they do it.

Aim

In this project, 6 participants were asked to perform barbell lifts correctly and incorrectly in 5 different ways. The data from accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm, and dumbell will be used to predict how well the barbell lifts were performed. The data used for this analysis was previously divided as training set and the test set to predict. These data are based on the study Human Activity Recognition.

Analysis

Initial setting

  • To guarantee reproducibility, the seed 452 was set.
  • The analysis requires the package caret (Classification And Regression Training) for model building
  • The data from the study was loaded and the training data was divided into train and validation datasets.
# Load required package
library(caret)
library(doParallel)

# Load the raw data
train.data <- read.csv("pml-training.csv", header=TRUE)
test.data <- read.csv("pml-testing.csv", header=TRUE)

# For reproducibility
set.seed(452)

# Divide the training data for validation
train_idx <- createDataPartition(train.data$classe, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
train <- train.data[train_idx, ]
validation <- train.data[-train_idx, ]

Data processing

The train data set was initially simplified by taking only the variables corresponding to the accelerometer values, since this analysis focuses in predicting the quality of the activity by using only the data from the accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm and dumbell.

train <- train[, c(accel, ncol(train))]

# Find incomplete variables

temp <- numeric()
for (i in 1:ncol(train)) {
    if(sum(is.na(train[,i]))!=0) {
        print(paste(i, names(train)[i], sep="   "))
        temp <- append(temp,i)
    }
}

Exploratory data analysis

The remaining variables were plotted to check their influence on the observed exercise quality (classe). Exercise quality is described as Classe A if it corresponds to the specified execution of the exercise, with the other 4 classes (B to E) correspond to common mistakes observed.

featurePlot(x=train[,1:4], y=train$classe, plot="box", labels = c('Exercise Quality Class', 'Accelerometer Values'), main = 'Accelerometer results for belt')

Model building

Before bulding the model, all remaining variables were converted into numeric values.

# Set all variables as numeric

for (i in 1:(ncol(train)-1)) {
    train[, i] <- as.numeric(train[, i])
}

Having simplified the train data and selected the most relevant variables, a random forest model (with k-fold cross-validation) was chosen to predict how well the the barbell lifts were performed. Random forests are powerful supervised algorithms that tend to be a very strong performers in a myriad of situations. The bagging of various Decisions tress, turn simple interpretable models into a “black box” model, lacking the transparency to fully understand how each variable affects the outcome. However, the aim of this exercise is not interpretation, but prediction and Random Forests are able to classify non-linear relationships such as those expected between the accelerometer values and the exercise quality categories.

cl <- makePSOCKcluster(detectCores())
registerDoParallel(cl)

trControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3, search="random")
model <- train(classe ~ ., data = train, method = "rf", prox = TRUE, tuneLength  = 15, trControl = trControl)

stopCluster(cl)

The results of the model building suggest that sampling 3 random variables (mtry) at each decision (split) point results in the highest model accuracy.

In this case, the out-of-sample accuracy is 0.947, which is still very high, suggesting that the model performs well even when confronted with new data sets. Even though Random Forests are difficult to interpret, the relative importance of each variable can be extracted from the model.

varImp(model)

We can see that the most important variable is the z-value from the belt, which is not surprising since the studied exercises require a lifting movement. In contrast, the x- and y-values for the belt do not seem to be very important, which indicates that the belt movement is important for the lifting movement. In addition, all values for the dumbbell position are high on the importance list, suggesting that the way the dumbbell moves is critical for a correctly performed exercise.

Prediction

# Predict test data
(answers <- predict(model,test.data[,-160]))
##  [1] B A C A A E D B A A B C B A E E A B B B
## Levels: A B C D E

# Print results in the required format
pml_write_files = function(x){ 
    n = length(x)
    for(i in 1:n){ 
        filename = paste0("problem_id_", i, ".txt")
        write.table(x[i], file = filename, quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE)
}
}
pml_write_files(answers)
